identified in the mid-portion of the right lobe of the thyroid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT neck","Active surveillance","Right hemithyroidectomy","Total thyroidectomy","Radioiodine ablation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA papillary microcarcinoma (PMC) is considered an \u2018incidental thyroid carcinoma\u2019 as it was detected unexpectedly in tissue resected for a benign pathology. PMC is usually less than 1cm in diameter. Observational studies suggest that patients with these tumours do not need resection and can be kept under \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E. In this case, the tumour has been resected as part of another procedure and certainly no further intervention is needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith the increased use of various imaging tools, the incidence of \u201cthyroid cancer\u201d has increased dramatically over the last decade. Despite this increase in incidence, the mortality of the disease remains unchanged. This suggests that most of these newly diagnosed tumours are of little, if any, clinical significance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAggressive surgical approach such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eright hemithyroidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E and\u003Cstrong\u003E total thyroidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E risk complications such as bleeding, hypocalcaemia, recurrent or superior laryngeal nerve injury and thyroid storm. Other studies have shown that the long term results for patients with PMCs do not differ between those who undergo hemithyroidectomy or total thyroidectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Eradioiodine ablation \u003C/strong\u003Erisks the development of hypothyroidism. These approaches would be of limited, if any value, in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive surveillance for PMCs found after surgery has been introduced. The 2015 American Thyroid Association guidelines define the following patient eligibility for active surveillance:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epatients with very low-risk PMCs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epatients with comorbidities that render surgery high risk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epatients expected to have a relatively short life expectancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epatients with simultaneous medical or surgical problems that need to be addressed before thyroid surgery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients willing to accept an active surveillance approach should understand that surgical intervention may be necessary in the future and be compliant with follow-up plans. The Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Centre has recommended a strict protocol of\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Erepeat ultrasound every six months for the first two years and thereafter every year or two.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltrasound has become widely accepted as the first imaging technique used for the assessment of cervical lymph node metastasis in patients with papillary thyroid cancer. \u003Cstrong\u003ECT neck \u003C/strong\u003Emay be used as a complementary diagnostic tool.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small, incidental thyroid tumours can be managed by surveillance."],"references":["Nanjappa N, Kumar A, Swain SK, et al. Incidental thyroid carcinoma. Indian J Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2013 Jan;65(1):37-9.Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24381917/","Pezzolla A, Marzaioli R, Lattarulo S,. Incidental carcinoma of the thyroid. Int J Surg. 2014;12 Suppl 1:S98-102. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24866072/","Jeon MJ, Kim WG, Chung KW, et al. Active Surveillance of Papillary Thyroid Microcarcinoma: Where Do We Stand? Eur Thyroid J. 2019 Dec;8(6):298-306. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31934555/","Dobrinja C, Pastoricchio M, Trioan M, et al. Partial thyroidectomy for papillary thyroid microcarcinoma: Is completion total thyroidectomy indicated? Int J Surg 2017; S34-S39."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96586"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"218"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96586"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T20:32:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T20:32:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"218"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114583"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji"